Instead of maintaining two separate maps, we use one HashMap<Object, Integer>.
Object because we will store: Character (from pattern), String (word from s) as keys in the same map.

For every index i: We store the last seen index of: pattern.charAt(i) words[i]
If the previous index of both is not the same → pattern mismatch.
This works because:
If two pattern characters map to the same word, their previous indices will conflict.
If one character maps to two different words, indices will differ.

class Solution {
    public boolean wordPattern(String pattern, String s) {
        String[] words = s.split(" ");
        if (pattern.length() != words.length) return false;
        Map<Object, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
            char ch = pattern.charAt(i);
            String word = words[i];
            Integer charPrev = map.put(ch, i);
            Integer wordPrev = map.put(word, i);
            if (!Objects.equals(charPrev, wordPrev)){
                return false;}}
        return true;}}
